^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Very interesting hand. I don't blame Roberta one bit for doubling. I would have. The heart void is totally unexpected. Anyway, let me first touch on when to draw trumps. It used to be that most inexperienced players drew trumps too early. However, these days I have noticed many of my students do not draw trumps soon enough. I would say on about half the hands, you should draw trumps right away. Your first instinct should be to "get the kiddies off the street" by drawing trump. So, you have to have a good reason to not draw trumps.|
PG| ***** 140 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The most common reason to not draw trumps is that you have to ruff some cards in dummy before dummy runs out of triumps. With a 5-5 fit (and most often even with a 5-4 fit) it is usually right to draw trumps ASAP. On this hand in particular, Ann only needs 2 diamonds in dummy for her 2 clubs. Therefore, no matter how trumps break, there will be 2 diamonds in dummy. As a general rule, you should always draw trump unless there is a good reason not to. However, to be fair, on more than half the hands, there is good reason to delay drawing trumps but rarely on hands with 10 card fits.|
PG| ***** 141 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, lets talk about the bidding. Everything is fine through 2C. And 2D is fine, but conservative, I might try 3D with Ann's hand. As to Roberta's bid over 2D that is interesting. I think she should bid something stronger than 3C. 2S would be ok, showing a limit raise or better in clubs. 3D would be an interesting bid. In an expert partnership, that would be a splinter (since 2S is available as the strong raise). But, with less experienced partnerships, 2S is fine.|
PG| ***** 142 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, what about my bid? First of all I have a big advantage. I have already passed and partner should know I cannot have much in HCP. In general, if you take a slight underbid, limitiing your hand initially then you can bid a lot later on, as partner knows you have a limited hand. On this particular hand, I passed, so pard knows I cannot have many HCP. But once the auction proceeds my hand gets much better. My diamond support is great and my club void is also excellent.|
PG| ***** 143 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Using Bergen methodology, I can count 2 HCP (the @HJ is likely to be useless), 3 length points, 1 for doubleton spade, and 5 for club void. Remember voids are worth the number of trump you have. So, my crummy hand has grown to be worth 11 points which is why I was very confident bidding 4D. Also, although partner does not have to have 5, she often will. And, in that case, the bid makes sense by The Law of Total Tricks. As you see, we can make 5D with my "crummy" hand with only 16 HCP between us.|
